  <bioghist id="aspace_8d030be14ecbc4c23b951b52466b2691">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>Edwin C. Bearss (b. June 26, 1923) is a world renowned miltary historian specializing in Civil War and World War II history. He had a long and distinguished career with the National Park Service, including discovery of the long lost Union gunboat U.S.S. Cairo as well as locating two forts in Grand Gulf, Mississippi.</p><p>Over the course of his career Bearss conducted many detailed area studies for the National Park Service. Several of his most notable studies include, but are certainly not limited to: Vicksburg, Eisenhower Farm at Gettysburg, Fort Hancock at the Boston Nacy Yard, Lyndon B. Johnson Ranch, William Howard Taft House, and Big Horn Canyon.</p><p>Bearss served as Chief Historian for the National Park Service from 1981-1994.</p>  </bioghist>
